Issues.Body:
My `EditForm` with a `DataAnnotationsValidator` contains a custom `MyComponent` component. The minimal repro below is [published here](https://github.com/space-alien/DataAnnotationsValidatorIssue).

When the button in `MyComponent` is clicked, validation fires on the `EditForm`. This occurs even when none of the form fields have been modified, which is undesirable.

Is this behaviour expected? If so, how can I avoid the form validation being triggered by a change to the child component?

This is occurring in a Blazor Server project on .NET 6.0.3.

## Index.razor

```razor
@page "/"
@using System.ComponentModel.DataAnnotations

<EditForm Model="model">
    <DataAnnotationsValidator />
    <ValidationSummary />

    <label>
        Name:
        <InputText @bind-Value="model.Name" />
    </label>
    <MyComponent />
</EditForm>

@code {
    MyModel model = new();

    class MyModel
    {
        [Required]
        public string? Name { get; set; }
    }
}
```

## MyComponent.razor
```razor
<p>
    MyComponent: @(Switch ? "ON" : "OFF")

    <button @onclick="() => Switch = !Switch">Toggle</button>
</p>

@code {
    bool Switch = false;
}
```

### Is there an existing issue for this?

- [X] I have searched the existing issues

### Describe the bug

I have not been using .Net for ~4 years. So, the only .Net installations are coming from Windows Update (and maybe couple of VS 2019 updates).
Recently, Windows update started failing to install updates for .Net Core 3 and 5 and I started looking.

I's a complete mess.
There are 15+ versions installed.
Many have lost their installers in package Cache. (Remember I did not touch .Net for 4 years. It's breaking itself.)
Many of the versions are completely duplicated (e.g. having two "5.0.9 (x86)" versions installed with exact dame product name, but different IDs).

For the last many hours I've been doing the following: Hounding installer packages for .Net many products X many versions X CPU architectures.
Then:
* Installing (The products are already installed, but the installer exe often does not detect that)
* Repairing (Without repairing the uninstall does not uninstall everything)
* Uninstalling

And yet, even this does not always work.

Currently when I install Microsoft .NET Runtime - 5.0.12 (x64), it installs:
* Microsoft .NET Runtime - 5.0.12 (x64)
* Microsoft .NET Host - 5.0.12 (x64)
* Microsoft .NET Host FX Resolver - 5.0.12 (x64)

But when uninstalling, it only uninstalls the runtime.

Microsoft .NET Host
Microsoft .NET Host FX Resolver
Microsoft ASP.NET Core Shared Framework
Microsoft Windows Desktop Runtime
Microsoft .NET Core AppHost Pack
Microsoft .NET Core Host
Microsoft .NET Core Host FX Resolver
Microsoft .NET Core Runtime
Microsoft .NET Core Toolset

I've cleaned 2/3 of the mess. But there is still so much to do and many of these refuse to uninstall:

